05539nam a22006015i 9781400887415DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20171995nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008874157 a10.1515/97814008874152doi  a(DE-B1597)482041  a(OCoLC)1004877808  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aNAT0020002bisacsh04a599.8/21 aKummer, Hans, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn Quest of the Sacred Baboon :bA Scientist's Journey /cHans Kummer. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2017] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (364 p.) :b16 line drawings 34 halftones1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Legacy Library ;v519500tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATION CREDITS -- tMAP OF STUDY AREA -- tPREFACE. Return to Red Rock -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION. The Hamadryas Baboon: A Desert Saint and Lecher -- tCHAPTER ONE. The Zoo Baboons -- tCHAPTER TWO. On to Ethiopia -- tCHAPTER THREE. The One-Sided Marriage -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Tensions, Conventions, and Alliances among Males -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Life Histories -- tCHAPTER SIX. Experts in a Thorny Land -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Anatomy of the Social Relationship -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. The Net and the Sword -- tCHAPTER NINE. The Eye of the Beholder -- tCHAPTER TEN. Mahdi -- tCHAPTER ELEVEN. The Likely Evolution of Hamadryas Society: A Reconstruction and a Summary -- tCONCLUSION -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a tale that begins at a zoo in Zurich and takes us across the deserts of Ethiopia to the Asir Mountains in Saudi Arabia, Hans Kummer recreates the adventure and intellectual thrill of the early days of field research on primates. Just as Jane Goodall and Dian Fossey introduced readers to the fascinating lives of chimpanzees and gorillas, Kummer brings us face to face with the Hamadryas baboon. With their furry white mantles and gleaming red hindquarters, the Hamadryas appear frequently in the art of the ancient Egyptians--who may have interpreted the baboons' early morning grooming rituals as sun-worshiping rites. Back then, Hamadryas were thought to be incarnates of Thoth, the god of wisdom; today they are considered to have one of the most highly structured social systems among primates, very close, in some respects, to that of humans. In the 1960s, Kummer, after conflicts with nomadic warriors, managed to track down these elusive baboons near the Danakil Desert, and then followed them from dawn to dusk on their treks from one feeding place to another. His scientific account of this period reads like a travel memoir as he describes his encounters with the Hamadryas and the people with whom they share the desert. Winding his way through cliffs and stubble, Kummer records the baboons' social life, from the development of pair relationships to the way an entire group decides where to march each day. Much like the human nomads who cope with the harsh demands of the desert environment, the Hamadryas maintain a society that is strict and patriarchal in its details but multilayered and flexible in its largest units. We learn, for example, of the Hamadryas' respect for possession that protects family structure and of the cohesion among family leaders that lessens the threat of battle. At the same time, clear-cut personalities emerge from Kummer's account, drawing us into the life stories and power struggles of individual baboons. Whereas this rich detail holds many implications for natural scientists, the colorful way it comes to life makes for a compelling book bound to entertain and educate all readers.Originally published in 1995.The Princeton Legacy Library uses the latest print-on-demand technology to again make available previously out-of-print books from the distinguished backlist of Princeton University Press. These editions preserve the original texts of these important books while presenting them in durable paperback and hardcover editions. The goal of the Princeton Legacy Library is to vastly increase access to the rich scholarly heritage found in the thousands of books published by Princeton University Press since its founding in 1905.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aNATURE / Animals / Primates.2bisacsh1 aBiederman-Thorson, M. Ann.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400887415zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400887415423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400887415.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK